</ul><h1>Hold This For Me</h1><p>Halloween is behind us, which means we can begin relentlessly talking about ‘the holiday season’ without concern! (Although, honestly, we might be late to the party; seriously, there have already been more Christmas-themed commercials than usual, haven’t there?)</p>
<p>What do these things have to do with the holidays? Well, they’re convenient to have if you’re doing a bunch of driving to and from your relatives’ homes for Thanksgiving and such. Basically, you put one in your cupholder and bada-bing: you’ve got a phone mount without having to, you know, mount anything.</p>
<p>Which means the only thing for you to do is find some podcasts to fill all of those hours on the road.</p>
<p>Well, you’re in luck! We’ve got recommendations!</p>
<p>If you’re looking to kill some time in the car this holiday season, listen to these killer pods!</p>
<p><strong>Tree Degrees Removed From Murder</strong></p>
<p>While investigating his family tree, freelance journalist Hal Summer discovers something interesting: the third cousin of his grandfather lived in the small town of Cresthook, Alabama for exactly five years. And during those five years, six people disappeared. After he moved, the disappearances suddenly stopped. Could it be that Hal Summers has stumbled upon a serial killer… in his own family?</p>
<p><strong>The End of Summer</strong></p>
<p>Freelance journalist Gil Turner thinks he’s found the perfect podcast to quench his thirst for true crime: <em>Tree Degrees Removed From Murder</em>. It only has five reviews, but it was clearly the painstaking work of a perfectionist. Then, after just three episodes, the podcast ceases. What could have happened? Did host Hal Summer simply give up? Or did something far more nefarious occur? Gil Turner dives deep to tell the untold story.</p>
<p><strong>Gone Gil</strong></p>
<p>Gil Turner garnered tens of five-star reviews across podcast platforms for his thrilling podcast, <em>The End of Summer</em>. And at its conclusion, he promised more content to come. But then… silence. Erin Donaldson (a freelance journalist) investigates where Gil might have gone in this thrilling true crime podcast.</p>
<p><strong>A Case of the Murder Mondays</strong></p>
<p>Hal Summer, Gil Turner, and Erin Donaldson read the wikipedia pages about various murders and make crude jokes, to the delight of their twelve-million subscribers.</p>
<p>They sound great, don’t they? So listen while you drive. And have your phone in a convenient position to boot, with this 2-pack of Bulbhead CupCall Cup Holder Phone Mounts.</p>